<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[264,1324,1713,1899]" lastBlockId="2.[264,1323,284,350]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="3" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,384,1713,1739]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis</emphasis>
.— All 
<taxonomicName box="[479,641,1714,1739]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Tergoceracris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[479,641,1714,1739]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Tergoceracris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to the 
<taxonomicName box="[868,997,1714,1739]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Tergoceracris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cerropunta">
<emphasis box="[868,997,1714,1739]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">cerropunta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1060,1195,1714,1739]" class="Insecta" family="Baissogryllidae" genus="Tergoceracris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luquillensis">
<emphasis box="[1060,1195,1714,1739]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">luquillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which are shown in 
<figureCitation box="[378,459,1753,1779]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[264,368,823,847]" captionText="FIGURE 1. Portrait of Tergoceracris cerropuntamale." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Figs. 
<number box="[444,459,1753,1779]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[515,533,1753,1779]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[264,368,1319,1343]" captionText="FIGURE 2. Portrait of Tergoceracris luquillensisale." pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<number box="[515,533,1753,1779]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
. The genus is distinguished from all other Hispaniolan and Neotropical acridids by its heavily sclerotized, exaggeratedly long, and vertically elevated furculaein the males. No other grasshopper with similarly developed furculae is known to us. Another unique character that distinguishes both sexes is a dark annular area on the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[328,401,284,310]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="13.[264,368,848,872]" captionTargetBox="[413,1175,320,826]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[413,1175,320,826]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 4. Dorsal view of pronotum in T. ocampensis showing annular mark characteristic of the genus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/156980/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Fig. 
<number box="[384,401,284,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
), which is centrally light colored and demarcated by concentric light colored bands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
